&quot;fr-BE&quot; isn&#39;t fully supported, currently. You can see the supported languages [here](https://github.com/microsoft/Recognizers-Text/blob/master/.NET/Microsoft.Recognizers.Text/Culture.cs).

Now, the real reason that locale isn&#39;t working in your example is that you&#39;re setting it manually with:

```csharp
stepContext.Context.Activity.Locale = &quot;fr-BE&quot;;
```

...and this doesn&#39;t get applied to `ConfirmPrompt`. Instead, you need the **client** to set the locale. It&#39;s different for every client, but for WebChat, you&#39;d use something like:

```js
window.WebChat.renderWebChat(
    {
        directLine: window.WebChat.createDirectLine({
            token: &#39;YOUR_DIRECT_LINE_TOKEN&#39;
        }),
        locale: &#39;fr-FR&#39;, // CHANGE ME
    },
    document.getElementById(&#39;webchat&#39;)
    );
```

For Emulator, you set the locale in Settings:

[![enter image description here][1]][1]

---

Also note that ConfirmPrompt [has a `DefaultLocale`](https://github.com/microsoft/botbuilder-dotnet/blob/master/libraries/Microsoft.Bot.Builder.Dialogs/Prompts/ConfirmPrompt.cs#L51) setting that makes it so that if locale is not supplied at all on an activity, it defaults to whatever you set. WebChat and Emulator both will set `en-US` by default, therefore `ConfirmPrompt.DefaultLocale` will not work with WebChat/Emulator.

  [1]: https://i.stack.imgur.com/i9inO.png

